earspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=megaloman84>Megaloman84</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 22<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/27/03 11:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   What if we are alone?</span><hr size=1> We are all familiar with the Fermi paradox.  If life is so plentiful, why haven't we heard from them?<br>
<br>
It seems logical that if there were any reasonably large number of space faring civilizations, they would be all over the place.  If the average lifetimes were long enough, as there is no reason they should not be, I imagine space faring civilizations are rather hard to exterminate, then they should be literally piled on top of us.<br>
<br>
At the very least, we should be able to pick up their radio signatures or the telltale traces of their interstellar spaceships.  Star travel is, after all, one of the most energy intensive activities a race can engage in, some of that radiation should be visible from earth.<br>
<br>
There are a number of possible explanations.  The one I chose to consider here is, what if we are first?<br>
<br>
Given the nature of time, someone has to be first.  Every technological civilization would conclude logically that the chances of being first are so infinitesimally small as to be inconsequential, even the first.  They would wonder at the lack of other intelligent life and generate their own &quot;fermi paradox&quot;.  <br>
<br>
It is true that the probability of earth being the first planet in this galaxy to produce intelligent, technological life is tiny.  But statistical probability is meaningless if you are the statistic.<br>
<br>
The amount of comfort that a plane crash victim, plummeting to the ground, is able to derive from the statistical fact that air travel is the safest mode of transportation is probably minimal.<br>
<br>
In the end, we are just as likely to be the first technological civilization as any other, small as this chance may be.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 2081<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/27/03 12:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/zaphod3.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What if we are alone?</span><hr size=1> There would be some comfort in knowing that we are the most technologically advanced species in our part of the universe... it would be insurance against a more war like race (if there is a more war like race than us humans).<br>
<br>
But, if we eventually learn to travel to, and colonize other star systems, then won't we eventually become the aliens?  Different environments may cause the human settlers to adapt physically.  A lighter gravity planet may cause people to grow taller, or a slightly heavier gravity may produce the equivalent to the mythical Dwarves in the Lord of the Rings movies.  Perhaps over time the divergence may become so severe that inter-breeding is no longer possible? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>spacefaring rodent</span><br>  Posts: 1049<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/27/03 3:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What if we are alone?</span><hr size=1> I wouldn't be surprised if we're the only civilization in this galaxy to be technologically advanced enough for spaceflight.  I guess it might be pompous to make such a statement but I believe intelligent life that develops the capability for building advanced technology is probably extremely rare in the universe.  Of course I couldn't back that up with any evidence except to cite the paradox.  And even if we are the only ones capable of leaving our home planet in the galaxy and life is truly very very rare, it would dissolve a lot of ethical dilemnas for doing things like terraforming and colonizing extrasolar planets in general.  So to make a long story short, it would be fascinating to find ET civilizations, but I don't think such a discovery is the silver bullet that will compell us to get into space ourselves.  It could have just the opposite effect.   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 2/27/03 3:11:16 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=spacedrive@nuclearspace>Spacedrive</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 60<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/27/03 5:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   ET</span><hr size=1> The odds of us existing at the same time as another ET intelligence are extremely low. Even if Alpha Centauri A had an intelligent species on one of it's not-yet-detected planets it's likely that their civilization has come and gone. The star is 1-1.5 billion years older than our sun. They could have had a galaxy-spanning empire that endured for 100 million years and there would be absolutely no trace of them left. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=drcarstairs>DrCarstairs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Utterly Mad Scientist</span><br>  Posts: 172<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/28/03 3:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/pubimage.asp?id_=1690525 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Eternity must End!</span><hr size=1> I have often wondered about this myself, and there is only one-way to be sure – we have to get out there and find out!<br>
<br>
I think intelligence is inevitable though. Life expands, it grows. Life on earth has reached every point it can. The only way life can continue to expand is to get off of the earth, and the only way to do that is to have an intelligence do it (that would be us).<br>
<br>
Now, life on other planets (should it exists, and I am fairly sure it must) will try and do the same thing. But if we are alone, if the universe is sterile save for us, it is incumbent upon us to expand - if we don’t we doom not only ourselves but our progeny and every other form of life both current and to come to extinction.<br>
<br>
Back to the Classics, anyone remember Azimov's “End of Eternity”? A great book in which a bloated buercracy that controls time travel (Eternity) uses its power to manipulate humanity to keep it safe. In the end humanity dies out because by keeping them safe they kept them from exploring and growing; even though humanity was one of the first intelligent species, by the time they finally begin to expand they find space filled with no place for them. The book concerns humans (well, a human) from the very end of time trying to destroy Eternity and give humanity a chance. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/alien.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
